{
  "body": "From the [syntax doc](https://docs.perl6.org/language/syntax#Separating_Statements):\r\n\r\n> A closing curly brace followed by a newline character implies a statement separator, which is why you don't need to write a semicolon after an if statement block.\r\n\r\nBut this is not true. The closing curly in an uncuddled if-else won't imply a statement separator. The actual rule is that the end of a statement followed by vertical whitespace implies a statement separator. But, a statement can be anything that Perl 6 decides is a statement. \r\n\r\nSee [Is Perl 6's uncuddled else a special case for statement separation?](https://stackoverflow.com/q/45520479/2766176)",
